planation":"\u003Cp\u003EPseudopods are temporary cytoplasmic extensions that allow amoeboid movement through a process of extending and retracting these projections, enabling the organism to move and engulf food particles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtozoan parasites use different cellular structures for movement:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBalantidium coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is covered in cilia which enable movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E moves by extending pseudopods, making it a true amoeba.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELeishmania donovani\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E uses a single flagellum for movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E uses multiple flagella for locomotion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETrypanosoma brucei\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E moves using an undulating membrane with a flagellum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Entamoeba histolytica is a protozoan that moves using pseudopods (amoeboid movement).","Leishmania, Trypanosoma, and Trichomonas all use flagella for movement.","Balantidium coli uses cilia for movement."],"references":["Atlas, R. M., \u0026 Snyder, J. W. (2013). Handbook of media for clinical and public health microbiology. CRC Press","Van Haastert PJ. How cells use pseudopods for persistent movement and navigation. Sci Signal. 2011 Feb 8;4(159):pe6. doi: 10.1126/scisignal.2001708. PMID: 21304158.","Van Haastert PJ. Amoeboid cells use protrusions for walking, gliding and swimming. PLoS One. 2011;6(11):e27532. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0027532. Epub 2011 Nov 9. PMID: 22096590; PMCID: PMC3212573."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49672"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14861"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49672"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T10:19:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T10:20:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7552"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64240"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"